The World Health Organisation (WHO) has said except in cases of hemorrhagic fevers such as Ebola, Marburg and cholera, dead bodies of COVID-19 victims are generally not infectious. WHO said this in its interim guidance on infection prevention and Control for safe management of a dead body in the context of COVID-19. It said that only the lungs of patients with pandemic influenza, if handled improperly during an autopsy, could be infectious. WHO also clarified that coronaviruses cannot travel on radio waves or mobile networks, saying the virus is a respiratory disease. WHO in a statement yesterday debunked the myth, adding that COVID-19 was spread through respiratory droplets when an infected person coughs, sneezes or speaks. “People can also be infected by touching a contaminated surface and then their eyes, mouth or nose,” it said. WHO added that COVID-19 was spreading in many countries that do not have 5G mobile networks.